\par \hich\af0\dbch\af36\loch\f0 MEHEMMED ALI PASHA, the victorious pacificator of Egypt and Arabia, is already renowned in the civilized world. Egy\hich\af0\dbch\af36\loch\f0 
pt, once the home of discord and the headquarters of anarchy, under his administration has long enjoyed peace and prosperity; is permeable in all directions, and in perfect safety to the merchant and the traveler, and is yearly progressing in wealth and i
\hich\af0\dbch\af36\loch\f0 m\hich\af0\dbch\af36\loch\f0 provement.}{\cs16\f0\super\insrsid11228189\charrsid16408944 \chftn {\footnote \pard\plain \s15\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid16408944 
\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\loch\af36\hich\af36\dbch\af36\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\cs16\f0\fs24\super\insrsid16324536\charrsid15156991 \chftn }{\f0\fs24\insrsid16324536\charrsid15156991 \hich\af0\dbch\af36\loch\f0 
 For instance, a navigable passage has been cut through the rocks of the First Cataract, and a canal is at present constructing, by order of the Pasha, round some of the most difficult passes of the Second. He has completed a broad and deep canal from 
\hich\af0\dbch\af36\loch\f0 
the Nile to Alexandria, by which commerce is liberated from the risk attending the passage of the Boghaz of Rosetta. Large establishments for the fabric of saltpeter, gunpowder, cannon and small arms, others for the fabric of silks, cotton and sugar, have
\hich\af0\dbch\af36\loch\f0  \hich\af0\dbch\af36\loch\f0 been erected by the Viceroy, and are in operation under the superintendence of Europeans.}}}{\f0\insrsid11228189\charrsid16408944 
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af36\loch\f0 The Viceroy has been particularly attentive to revive and extend those commercial relations of Egypt with the surrounding countries, which once rendered it the richest and most flourishing  territory in the ancient world.

\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af36\loch\f0 A well chosen librar\hich\af0\dbch\af36\loch\f0 
y of the best European books on the art military, geography, astronomy, medicine, history, belles-lettres and the fine arts has been purchased from Europe by the Viceroy and placed in the palace of Ismael Pasha, where is also a school, at the Viceroy's ex
\hich\af0\dbch\af36\loch\f0 p\hich\af0\dbch\af36\loch\f0 
ense, for the instruction of the Mussulman youth in the Italian language and the sciences of the Franks. To which establishments has been lately added a printing press, for printing books in the Turkish, Arabic and Persian languages, and a weekly newspape
\hich\af0\dbch\af36\loch\f0 r\hich\af0\dbch\af36\loch\f0 
 in Arabic and Italian. The library and the press are under the superintendence of Osman Noureddin Effendi, a young Turk of great good sense, and who is well versed in the literature of Europe, where he has resided for several years, by order of the Vicer
\hich\af0\dbch\af36\loch\f0 o\hich\af0\dbch\af36\loch\f0 y, for his education: he is at present engaged in translating into Turkish some works on tactics, for the use of his countrymen.
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af36\loch\f0 For several years past the inland commerce of this favored land had suffered great interruptions from the confusion and discor\hich\af0\dbch\af36\loch\f0 
d to which the countries on the Upper Nile have been a prey. The chiefs of Shageia had formed themselves into a singular aristocracy of brigands, and pillaged all the provinces and caravans within their reach, without mercy and without restraint; while th
\hich\af0\dbch\af36\loch\f0 e\hich\af0\dbch\af36\loch\f0 
 civil wars, which have distracted the once powerful kingdom of Sennaar for these last eighteen years, had occasioned an almost entire cessation of a commerce, from which Egypt had derived great advantages.
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af36\loch\f0 His Highness the Viceroy, in consequence, determ\hich\af0\dbch\af36\loch\f0 ined, as the most effectual means of putting an end to these disorders, to subject those countries to his dominion.
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af36\loch\f0 Four thousand troops were accordingly put under the command of Ismael Pasha, the youngest son of the Viceroy, with  orders to conquer all t\hich\af0\dbch\af36\loch\f0 
he provinces on the Nile, from the Second Cataract to Sennaar inclusive.
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af36\loch\f0 Through the influence of the recommendation of Henry Salt, Esq., His Britannic Majesty's Consul General in Egypt, I was ordered by the Viceroy to accompany this expedition, with the \hich\af0\dbch\af36\loch\f0 
rank of Topgi Bashi, i.e. a chief of artillery, and with directions to propose such plans of operation to the Pasha Ismael as I should deem expedient, but which the Pasha might adopt or reject as he should think proper.
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af36\loch\f0 This expedition has been perfectly \hich\af0\dbch\af36\loch\f0 
successful; and the conquest of the extensive and fertile countries, which, in the reign of Candace, repulsed the formidable legions of Rome, has been effected at an expense not greater than the blood of about two hundred soldiers.
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af36\loch\f0 The principal cause of \hich\af0\dbch\af36\loch\f0 
a success so extraordinary, at such a price, has been the humanity and good faith of the Pasha Ismael towards those provinces that submitted without fighting. Perfect security of person and property was assured to the peaceable, and severe examples were m
\hich\af0\dbch\af36\loch\f0 a\hich\af0\dbch\af36\loch\f0 
de of those few of the soldiery, who, in a very few instances, presumed to violate it. The good consequences of this deportment toward the people of these countries have been evident. All have seen that those who have preferred peace before war have had p
\hich\af0\dbch\af36\loch\f0 e\hich\af0\dbch\af36\loch\f0 ace without war, and that those who preferred war before peace have not had peace but at the price of ruin.
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af36\loch\f0 The destruction or disarmament of the brigands, who have heretofore pillaged those countries with impunity--the establishment of order and tranquil\hich\af0\dbch\af36\loch\f0 
ity--the security now assured to the peasants and the caravans--and the annexment of so many fine provinces and kingdoms to the sway of the Viceroy of Egypt}{\f0\insrsid2556482\charrsid16408944 \hich\af0\dbch\af36\loch\f0 ,}{
